# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2000-united-states-census
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:2000-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:2000-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:2000-united-states-census/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The **2000 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau, determined the resident population of the United States on April 1, 2000, to be 281,421,906, an increase of 13.2 percent over the 248,709,873 people enumerated during the 1990 census.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] This was the twenty-second federal census and was at the time the largest civilly administered peacetime effort in the United States.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Approximately 16 percent of households received a "long form" of the 2000 census, which contained over 100 questions.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] It would be the last census to include the "long form", since subsequent censuses, starting with the 2010 census, would be "short form" only, with the more detailed questions being replaced by the new American Community Survey.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Full documentation on the 2000 census, including census forms and a procedural history, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a state—California—recorded a population of over 30 million, as well as the first in which two states—California and Texas—recorded populations of more than 20 million.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Microdata from the 2000 census is freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2072.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The U.S. resident population includes the total number of people in the 50 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The Bureau also enumerated the residents of the U.S. territory of Puerto Rico; its population was 3,808,610, an 8.1% increase over the number from a decade earlier.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Regionally, the South and West experienced the bulk of the nation's population increase: 14,790,890 and 10,411,850, respectively.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] This meant that the mean center of U.S. population moved to Phelps County, Missouri.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The Northeastern United States grew by 2,785,149; the Midwest by 4,724,144.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The results of the census are used to determine how many congressional districts each state is apportioned.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Congress defines the formula, in accordance with Title 2 of the U.S.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Code, to reapportion among the states the 435 seats in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The apportionment population consists of the resident population of the fifty states, plus the overseas military and federal civilian employees and their dependents living with them who could be allocated to a state.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Each member of the House represents a population of about 647,000.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The populations of the District of Columbia and Puerto Rico are excluded from the apportionment population because they do not have voting seats in the U.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Since the first census in 1790, the decennial count has been the basis for the United States representative form of government.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Article I, Section II specifies that "The Number of Representatives shall not exceed one for every thirty Thousand, but each State shall have at Least one Representative." In 1790, each member of the House represented about 34,000 residents.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Since then, the House more than quadrupled in size, and in 1911 the number of representatives was fixed at 435.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Today, each member represents about 20 times as many constituents.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] In the years leading up to the 2000 census, there was substantial controversy over whether the Bureau should adjust census figures based on a follow-up survey, called the post-enumeration survey, of a sample of blocks.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] This recommendation was followed by the Secretary of Commerce (the official in charge of making the determination).
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] After the census was tabulated, Utah challenged the results in two different ways.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Utah was extremely close to gaining a fourth congressional seat, falling 857 people short, which in turn was allocated to North Carolina.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The margin was later shortened to 80 people, after the federal government discovered that it overcounted the population of North Carolina by 2,673 residents.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The Census Bureau counted members of the military and other federal civilian employees serving abroad as residents of their home state but did not count other people living outside the United States.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Utah claimed that people traveling abroad as religious missionaries should be counted as residents and that the failure to do so imposed a burden on Mormon religious practice.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Almost half of all Mormon missionaries, more than 11,000 people, were from Utah; only 102 came from North Carolina.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] If this policy were changed, then Utah would have received an additional seat instead of North Carolina.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] On November 26, 2002, the Supreme Court affirmed the lower court ruling that rejected Utah's efforts to have Mormon missionaries counted.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The state of Utah then filed another lawsuit alleging that the statistical methods used in computing the state populations were improper and cost Utah the seat.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The Bureau uses a method called imputation to assign a number of residents to addresses where residents cannot be reached after multiple efforts.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] While nationwide the imputation method added 0.4% to the population, the rate in Utah was 0.2%.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The state challenged that the use of imputation violates the Census Act of 1957 and that it also fails the Constitution's requirement in Article I, Section 2 that an "actual enumeration" be used for apportionment.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Evans*, made it to the Supreme Court, but Utah was again defeated.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The census forms did not include any questions regarding sexual orientation, making it impossible to compile data comparing heterosexual and homosexual populations.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] However, two questions *were* asked that allowed same-sex partnerships to be counted.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The questionnaires asked the sex of each person in a household and they asked what the relationship was between each of the members of the household.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Respondents could check "Husband/wife" or "unmarried partner" or a number of other relationships.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Responses were tabulated and the Census Bureau reported that there were more than 658,000 same-sex couples heading households in the United States.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] However, only about 25% of gay men and 40% of lesbians are in shared-household partnerships at any one time, according to non-census surveys.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] For every same-sex couple tallied in the census, there could be three to six more homosexual un-partnered individuals who would not be counted as gay.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The census reported that same-sex male couples numbered 336,001 and female same-sex couples numbered 329,522.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Extrapolating from those figures and the surveyed partnering habits of homosexuals, as many as 4.3 million homosexual adults could have been living in the U.S. in 2000.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The exact number cannot be known because the census did not count them specifically.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Bisexual and transgender populations were not counted, either, because there were no questions regarding this information.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Also unavailable is the number of additional same-sex couples living under the same roof as the first, though this applies to additional heterosexual couples as well.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The lack of accurate numbers makes it difficult for lawmakers who are considering legislation on hate crimes or social services for gay families with children.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] It also makes for less accuracy when predicting the fertility of a population.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Another issue that concerned gay rights advocates involved the automatic changing of data during the tabulation process.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] This automatic software data compiling method, called *allocation*, was designed to counteract mistakes and discrepancies in returned questionnaires.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] Forms that were filled out by two same-sex persons who checked the "Husband/wife" relationship box were treated as a discrepancy.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The Census Bureau explained that same-sex "Husband/wife" data samples were changed to "unmarried partner" by computer processing methods in 99% of the cases.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] In the remaining 1%, computer systems used one of two possibilities: a) one of the two listed sexes was changed, making the partnership appear heterosexual, or b) if the two partners were more than 15 years apart in age, they might have been reassigned into a familial parent/child relationship.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] The process of automatic reassignment of same-sex marriage data was initiated so that the Census Bureau would not contravene the Defense of Marriage Act passed in 1996.
[src:2000-united-states-census/2000-united-states-census] With allocation moving married same-sex couples to the unmarried partner category, social scientists lost information that could have been extracted relating to the social stability of a same-gender couple who identify themselves as married.
